teachingSummary:
**Core Rule:** The Unfair Contract Terms Act 1977 (UCTA) imposes statutory controls on exclusion and limitation clauses. Even if a clause is properly incorporated and favourably construed, it may be rendered ineffective by UCTA. The Act applies a test of reasonableness to exclusion clauses and imposes outright bans in certain circumstances.

**Section 2(1) — Death or Personal Injury:** A person cannot, by reference to any contract term or notice, exclude or restrict liability for death or personal injury resulting from negligence. This is an absolute prohibition — no exclusion of liability for negligently caused death or personal injury is permitted under any circumstances.

**Section 2(2) — Other Loss:** Liability for other loss or damage caused by negligence can be excluded or restricted only insofar as the term satisfies the requirement of reasonableness.

**Section 3 — Standard Terms:** Where one party deals as consumer or on the other party's written standard terms of business, the other cannot exclude or restrict liability for breach of contract except insofar as the term satisfies the requirement of reasonableness.

**Section 11 — The Reasonableness Test:** The term must have been a fair and reasonable one to include, having regard to all circumstances known to or contemplated by the parties at the time of contracting. The burden of proving reasonableness lies on the party relying on the clause.

**Schedule 2 Guidelines:** When applying the reasonableness test, the court must consider:
(a) The relative strength of the parties' bargaining positions;
(b) Whether the customer received an inducement to agree to the term;
(c) Whether the customer knew or ought reasonably to have known of the term;
(d) Where the term excludes liability if a condition is not complied with — whether compliance was reasonably practicable;
(e) Whether the goods were manufactured, processed or adapted to the customer's special order.

**In short:** UCTA 1977 provides a statutory overlay. Section 2(1) is absolute (no exclusion of liability for death/personal injury from negligence). Otherwise, the reasonableness test — guided by the Schedule 2 factors — controls.
